SIMPLE: malignant
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: malignant
<hw>ma*lig"nant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>malignans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>malignare</ets>,
<ets>malignari</ets>, to do or make maliciously. See <er>Malign</er>,
and cf. <er>Benignant</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Disposed to do harm,
inflict suffering, or cause distress; actuated by extreme malevolence or
enmity; virulently inimical; bent on evil; malicious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>malignant</qex> and a turbaned Turk.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Characterized or caused by evil intentions;
pernicious.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Malignant</xex> care.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some <qex>malignant</qex> power upon my life.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Something deleterious and <qex>malignant</qex> as his touch.</q>
<rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Tending to produce death;
threatening a fatal issue; virulent; <as>as, <ex>malignant</ex>
diphtheria</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Malignant pustule</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a very
contagious disease produced by infection of subcutaneous tissues with
the bacterium <spn>Bacillus anthracis</spn>. It is transmitted to man
from animals and is characterized by the formation, at the point of
reception of the infection, of a vesicle or pustule which first enlarges
and then breaks down into an unhealthy ulcer. It is marked by profound
exhaustion and often fatal. The disease in animals is called
<altname>charbon</altname>; in man it is called <altname>cutaneous
anthrax</altname>, and formerly was sometimes called simply
<altname>anthrax</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malignant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Malignant
<hw>Ma*lig"nant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A man
of extreme enmity or evil intentions.</def>
<rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eng. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of the adherents of
<person>Charles I.</person> or <person>Charles II.</person>; -- so
called by the opposite party.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malignant anemia</ent>⟦br⟧
